      <hedline>
        <hl1>West Nile Alert</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Florence Krinsky letter disputes August 4 article on West Nile virus outbreak in New York area</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In an Aug. 4 news article, you give an update on the West Nile virus situation, repeating the message of the New York State public service announcement that urges the public to get rid of standing water ''around their homes.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In an Aug. 4 news article, you give an update on the West Nile virus situation, repeating the message of the New York State public service announcement that urges the public to get rid of standing water ''around their homes.''</p>
        <p>But in New York City, judging by an inspection of a number of Upper West Side streets, some standing water has been caused by malfunctioning street drains. Dealing with this is the responsibility, therefore, of the proper city department, and not of the public.</p>
        <p>If the city is serious about getting rid of mosquitoes, the problem of the drains that don't work should be addressed immediately. The establishment of a hot line through which people can identify the streets where standing water can be found would help to carry out this action.</p>
        <p>FLORENCE KRINSKY  New York, Aug. 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
